<p><a name="Notes" id="Notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Tragedy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="references-small references-column-count references-column-count-2" style="-moz-column-count:2; column-count:2;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> Banham (1998, 1118). In his speculative work on the origins of <a href="/wiki/Theatre_of_ancient_Greece" title="Theatre of ancient Greece">Athenean tragedy</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Birth_of_Tragedy" title="The Birth of Tragedy">The Birth of Tragedy</a></i> (1872), <a href="/wiki/Friedrich_Nietzsche" title="Friedrich Nietzsche">Nietzsche</a> writes of this "two-fold mood": "the strange mixture and duality in the affects of the <a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysiac</a> <a href="/wiki/Cult_of_Dionysus" title="Cult of Dionysus">enthusiasts</a>, that phenomenon whereby pain awakens pleasure while rejoicing wrings cries of agony from the breast. From highest joy there comes a cry of horror or a yearning lament at some irredeemable loss. In those Greek festivals there erupts what one might call a <a href="/wiki/Sentimentality" title="Sentimentality">sentimental</a> tendency in nature, as if it had cause to sigh over its <a href="/wiki/Sparagmos" title="Sparagmos">dismemberment</a> into <a href="/wiki/Individuation" title="Individuation">individuals</a>" §2 (Speirs 1999, 21).</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Banham (1998, 1118) and Williams (1966, 14-16).</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> Williams (1966, 16).</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> Williams (1966, 13-84) and Taxidou (2004, 193-209).</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> See Dukore (1974) for primary material on most of these philosophers' writings on tragedy and Carlson (1993) for an analysis of them. <a href="/wiki/Walter_Benjamin" title="Walter Benjamin">Walter Benjamin</a>'s major work on tragic form is <i><a href="/wiki/Walter_Benjamin#The_Origin_of_German_Tragic_Drama" title="Walter Benjamin">The Origin of German Tragic Drama</a></i> (1928). <a href="/wiki/Gilles_Deleuze" title="Gilles Deleuze">Gilles Deleuze</a> develops his theory of tragic representation in his collaboration with <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Guattari" title="Félix Guattari">Félix Guattari</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Anti-%C5%92dipus" title="Anti-Œdipus">Anti-Œdipus</a></i> (1972).</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> See Carlson (1993), Pfister (1977), Elam (1980) and Taxidou (2004). <a href="/wiki/Drama" title="Drama">Drama</a>, in the narrow sense, cuts across the traditional division between comedy and tragedy in an anti- or a-<a href="/wiki/Genre" title="Genre">generic</a> <a href="/wiki/Deterritorialization" title="Deterritorialization">deterritorialization</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Nineteenth_century_theatre" title="Nineteenth century theatre" class="mw-redirect">mid-19th century</a> onwards. Both <a href="/wiki/Bertolt_Brecht" title="Bertolt Brecht">Bertolt Brecht</a> and <a href="/wiki/Augusto_Boal" title="Augusto Boal">Augusto Boal</a> define their <a href="/wiki/Epic_theatre" title="Epic theatre">epic theatre</a> projects (<a href="/wiki/Non-Aristotelian_drama" title="Non-Aristotelian drama">Non-Aristotelian drama</a> and <a href="/wiki/Theatre_of_the_Oppressed" title="Theatre of the Oppressed">Theatre of the Oppressed</a> respectively) against models of tragedy. Taxidou, however, reads epic theatre as an incorporation of tragic functions and its treatments of mourning and speculation (2004, 193-209).</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> P.W. Buckham, <i>Theatre of the Greeks,</i> p. 108</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> P.W. Buckham, ibid, p. 121, quoting from <i>Lectures on Dramatic Art and Literature</i> by <a href="/wiki/August_Wilhelm_von_Schlegel" title="August Wilhelm von Schlegel" class="mw-redirect">August Wilhelm von Schlegel</a><a href="http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/7148" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/7148" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> Aristotle, <i>Poetics</i>, IV, 1449a, "To consider whether tragedy is fully developed by now in all its various species or not, and to criticize it both in itself and in relation to the stage, that is another question. At any rate it originated in improvisation--both tragedy itself and comedy. The one tragedy came from the prelude to the dithyramb and the other <a href="/wiki/Comedy" title="Comedy">comedy</a> from the prelude to the phallic songs which still survive as institutions in many cities. Tragedy then gradually evolved as men developed each element that came to light and after going through many changes, it stopped when it had found its own natural form."<a href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Aristot.+Poet.+1449a" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Aristot.+Poet.+1449a" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> Ley (33-34)</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> quoted in Christopher Headington, Roy Westbrook and Terry Barfoot (1987) <i>Opera: a History</i> p.22 of 1991 Arrow edition</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> Headington et al. p.178</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Howard Barker. <i>Arguments for a Theatre.</i>(London: John Calder, 1989), 13.</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> Aristotle. <i><a href="/wiki/Poetics_(Aristotle)" title="Poetics (Aristotle)">Poetics</a></i>, Trans. W.H. Fyfe. Cambridge: Harvard UP, 1932. Section 1452b</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> Rorty, Amelie Oksenberg. <i><a href="/wiki/Literary_criticism" title="Literary criticism">Essays on Aristotle’s Poetics</a></i>. Princeton: Princeton UP, 1992. Page 178</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> <i>Poetics</i>, Aristotle</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> Aristotle, <i>Poetics</i>. Section 1135b</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Chiari" title="Chiari">Chiari</a>, <a href="/wiki/J" title="J">J</a>. <i>Landmarks of Contemporary Drama</i>. <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>: <a href="/wiki/Jenkins" title="Jenkins">Jenkins</a>, 1965. Page 41.</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18" title="">^</a></b> Banham (1998, 517).</li>
<li id="cite_note-Oldenberg-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Oldenberg_19-0" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Hermann_Oldenberg" title="Hermann Oldenberg">Hermann Oldenberg</a> (1922), <i>Das Mahabharata</i>, Göttingen</li>
<li id="cite_note-Saunders-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Saunders_20-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFSaunders1921">Saunders, Virginia (1921), "Some Literary Aspects of the Absence of Tragedy in the Classical Sanskrit Drama", <i><a href="/wiki/Journal_of_the_American_Oriental_Society" title="Journal of the American Oriental Society">Journal of the American Oriental Society</a></i> <b>41</b>: 152–6</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Some+Literary+Aspects+of+the+Absence+of+Tragedy+in+the+Classical+Sanskrit+Drama&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BJournal+of+the+American+Oriental+Society%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Saunders&amp;rft.aufirst=Virginia&amp;rft.au=Saunders%2C+Virginia&amp;rft.date=1921&amp;rft.volume=41&amp;rft.pages=152%E2%80%936&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Tragedy"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
